00:00:02.420 --> 00:00:07.005
Okay so the object today is to
wrap our arms around,

00:00:07.005 --> 00:00:11.860
not all but a good portion,
of the material covered.

00:00:11.860 --> 00:00:15.079
The book called,
Bottom Billion,

00:00:15.079 --> 00:00:19.569
is somewhat neglected in
today's discussion but should

00:00:19.569 --> 00:00:22.620
not be neglected in your essays.
 

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:30.868
Indeed, your essays will need
to take account of many of the

00:00:30.868 --> 00:00:36.880
things said by Paul Collier in
that book.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:40.365
First of all,
our topic slide here,

00:00:40.365 --> 00:00:46.209
you have to ask yourself first
what this guy believes that

00:00:46.209 --> 00:00:49.900
umbrella is going to do for him.
 

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:54.131
It's--and I'll show you the
subsequent slide in the

00:00:54.131 --> 00:00:57.940
appropriate place about what
happens next,

00:00:57.940 --> 00:01:03.951
but the gist of that slide is
that capitalism is a dynamic

00:01:03.951 --> 00:01:10.280
system which is always leaning
forward and is always within a

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:14.709
few months of leaning too far
forward.

00:01:14.709 --> 00:01:28.280
It is the nature of the system.
 

00:01:28.280 --> 00:01:32.900
Okay I'm going to begin by
revisiting the fundamentals,

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:37.040
these systems of ideas that we
began the term with,

00:01:37.040 --> 00:01:43.750
and then we'll look at some of
those system in greater detail.

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:51.220
Thomas Malthus,
Essay on Population,

00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:58.430
the thesis is that nearly
universal poverty is inevitable,

00:01:58.430 --> 00:02:02.920
because wherever productivity
increases,

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:08.808
population increases apace,
and the resources used for

00:02:08.808 --> 00:02:15.143
production have diminishing
returns as you invest more and

00:02:15.143 --> 00:02:16.810
more labor.
 

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:21.814
Malthus is obviously thinking
about farming,

00:02:21.814 --> 00:02:26.937
and farming in a small island
called England,

00:02:26.937 --> 00:02:29.150
and he's wrong.
 

00:02:29.150 --> 00:02:34.492
The world demographic
transition utterly contradicts

00:02:34.492 --> 00:02:39.079
his theory,
and the fact that birth rates

00:02:39.079 --> 00:02:45.532
and death rates might fall in
the precipitous way they did is

00:02:45.532 --> 00:02:52.092
the world demographic transition
and is a major key to why the

00:02:52.092 --> 00:02:56.610
world economy works the way it
does,

00:02:56.610 --> 00:03:01.086
because it produces an enormous
surplus of labor in the

00:03:01.086 --> 00:03:06.060
societies which pass through it
later rather than earlier.

00:03:06.060 --> 00:03:10.936
Similarly, if we look at Hans
Rosling's wonderful data

00:03:10.936 --> 00:03:16.640
animation which we used on the
first day of class relating life

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:23.199
expectancy to GDP per capita,
the world in the last 120 years

00:03:23.199 --> 00:03:28.400
has grown richer on average five
or six fold,

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:32.128
500% or 600%,
richer and healthier,

00:03:32.128 --> 00:03:38.360
longer lived so that there is a
human project,

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:43.567
a world human project in which
the best of capitalism

00:03:43.567 --> 00:03:47.490
participates,
and I think that's the

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:50.758
important upside to the topic.
 

00:03:50.758 --> 00:03:57.949
Adam Smith, "invisible
hand," and Smith has become

00:03:57.949 --> 00:04:04.409
in death a more famous figure
than he was in life,

00:04:04.409 --> 00:04:07.090
and a simpler figure.
 

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:10.871
The number of people who have
actually read Wealth of

00:04:10.871 --> 00:04:14.860
Nations or read it and
Theory of Moral Sentiment

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:19.192
is a tiny fraction of the people
who claim to organize all their

00:04:19.192 --> 00:04:24.564
thinking around Adam Smith,
and Adam Smith's invisible hand

00:04:24.564 --> 00:04:29.165
is a fragile thing which
operates not with giant

00:04:29.165 --> 00:04:32.384
corporations,
not with oligopolies,

00:04:32.384 --> 00:04:36.829
not with monopsonies,
it operates under conditions of

00:04:36.829 --> 00:04:40.100
perfect or near perfect
competition.

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:43.379
And the Porter Forces which we
have seen,

00:04:43.379 --> 00:04:48.120
direct competition,
the threat of new competition,

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:51.589
the threat of people moving to
substitute products,

00:04:51.589 --> 00:04:55.550
the power of suppliers and the
power of buyers to bargain,

00:04:55.550 --> 00:05:01.269
all five of those factors work
against the invisible hand.

00:05:01.269 --> 00:05:07.742
The whole point of the Porter
Forces is how business

00:05:07.742 --> 00:05:14.088
corporations avoid being
compelled to behave in the

00:05:14.088 --> 00:05:21.449
Smithian way of producing goods
and selling them at or near

00:05:21.449 --> 00:05:24.750
their marginal cost.
 

00:05:24.750 --> 00:05:32.134
Carl Marx and Joseph Schumpeter;
two great economists,

00:05:32.134 --> 00:05:35.608
two great thinkers,
Marx the founder of a

00:05:35.608 --> 00:05:39.833
revolutionary movement,
Schumpeter a banker,

00:05:39.833 --> 00:05:47.240
a Harvard professor,
a brilliant intellect;

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:51.199
two ways of looking at the same
thing.

00:05:51.199 --> 00:05:56.593
What these two guys agree on is
that capitalism is an inherently

00:05:56.593 --> 00:05:59.420
unstable forward-moving system.
 

00:05:59.420 --> 00:06:03.927
That the one thing of which
capitalism is incapable is

00:06:03.927 --> 00:06:07.672
standing still,
that like the bicyclist in my

00:06:07.672 --> 00:06:11.675
title slide,
capitalism always leans forward

00:06:11.675 --> 00:06:16.788
and always relies on events in
the future which are not

00:06:16.788 --> 00:06:18.209
predictable.
 

00:06:18.209 --> 00:06:22.329
Now where the two part ways is
that Marx is a determinist;

00:06:22.329 --> 00:06:27.069
Marx really thinks that he can
foretell the history of

00:06:27.069 --> 00:06:30.110
capitalism in its main outlines.
 

00:06:30.110 --> 00:06:35.310
And he was mistaken;
of that we can be sure.

00:06:35.310 --> 00:06:39.800
Schumpeter, on the other hand,
believed that the future of

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:43.029
capitalism is inherently
indeterminate.

00:06:43.029 --> 00:06:49.077
That there is much random
process, so much opportunity for

00:06:49.077 --> 00:06:53.266
unexpected innovation,
that the prediction of

00:06:53.266 --> 00:06:56.620
capital--the behavior of
capitalist economies,

00:06:56.620 --> 00:07:01.420
beyond the very short term,
is impossible,

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:06.041
and I'm inclined to believe
that Schumpeter's right about

00:07:06.041 --> 00:07:06.620
that.
 

00:07:06.620 --> 00:07:08.509
Hayek.
 

00:07:08.509 --> 00:07:12.769
Hayek is the guy who wrote
Constitution of Liberty,

00:07:12.769 --> 00:07:15.060
and it's possible to be very
critical of Hayek,

00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:18.449
who does play some logical
tricks with his reader.

00:07:18.449 --> 00:07:22.963
On the other hand,
he puts forward a passionate

00:07:22.963 --> 00:07:28.850
vision about the creative
possibilities of a free society.

00:07:28.850 --> 00:07:33.281
A society in which the right to
innovate the right to choose,

00:07:33.281 --> 00:07:37.711
the right to author ones own
life and propose scripts for the

00:07:37.711 --> 00:07:43.093
lives of others;
a society which is open and not

00:07:43.093 --> 00:07:50.778
subject to overbearing hierarchy
and bureaucracy is a learning

00:07:50.778 --> 00:07:56.019
machine,
and Hayek is a brilliant

00:07:56.019 --> 00:08:01.459
theorist of that learning
machine.

00:08:01.459 --> 00:08:05.889
Another set of fundamentals,
this is Ronald Coase,

00:08:05.889 --> 00:08:08.329
he of Coase theorem fame.
 

00:08:08.329 --> 00:08:11.600
This is Hernando de Soto,
he of Mystery of

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:16.982
Capitalism fame,
and what they both say is that

00:08:16.982 --> 00:08:23.470
capital formation relies on
governments and courts,

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:27.199
and the formalization of
property rights,

00:08:27.199 --> 00:08:31.824
and that one of the
foundational aspects of our

00:08:31.824 --> 00:08:38.058
wealth in the western world is
tradable property rights so that

00:08:38.058 --> 00:08:43.490
our houses are also small
storehouses of capital,

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:49.238
and our earning power can be
the collateral for debt which is

00:08:49.238 --> 00:08:52.399
repaid through future earnings.
 

00:08:52.399 --> 00:08:56.868
That whole aspect of
capitalism, that whole metabolic

00:08:56.868 --> 00:09:02.538
process is at the fundaments of
the best aspects of capitalism,

00:09:02.538 --> 00:09:07.200
the aspects that involve
sustained prosperity.

