talking about something
imaginary.

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:54.363
Now what an interesting
exercise to do is to single out

00:15:54.363 --> 00:16:02.750
some command economies such as
the Soviet Union before it--

00:16:02.750 --> 00:16:09.028
in 1989, or Cuba throughout the
last sixty years and watch them,

00:16:09.028 --> 00:16:13.765
and what you'll find is they do
relatively well on the health

00:16:13.765 --> 00:16:18.740
and longevity dimension and not
so well on the GDP dimension.

00:16:18.740 --> 00:16:22.942
It is perfectly reasonable for
someone to say,

00:16:22.942 --> 00:16:26.120
"I don't care about
wealth.

00:16:26.120 --> 00:16:30.320
I care about health and good
spirit and all that,

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:34.392
and I'm not interested in being
part of a society that generates

00:16:34.392 --> 00:16:37.690
enormous wealth,"
and there are very reasonable

00:16:37.690 --> 00:16:40.470
and rational people who take
that view.

00:16:40.470 --> 00:16:45.374
It's an option and its fine,
it's even admirable,

00:16:45.374 --> 00:16:51.298
but it's not what capitalist
market societies are about.

00:16:51.298 --> 00:16:56.532
One reasonable critique of
capitalist market societies is

00:16:56.532 --> 00:17:01.764
that they encourage us all to
consume way beyond our real

00:17:01.764 --> 00:17:02.700
needs.
 

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:07.118
That we spend more money on
clothing and automobiles and

00:17:07.118 --> 00:17:10.654
sporting equipment,
and liquor than is really

00:17:10.654 --> 00:17:13.950
needed, and there's no doubt of
that.

00:17:13.950 --> 00:17:18.795
I'm guilty myself,
and my guess is that most of

00:17:18.795 --> 00:17:24.798
you feel the pull of market
society and the inclination to

00:17:24.798 --> 00:17:29.644
spend more than would be
absolutely rational or

00:17:29.644 --> 00:17:31.329
necessary.
 

00:17:31.329 --> 00:17:35.523
Fair enough;
it's a critique,

00:17:35.523 --> 00:17:38.720
and I think it's a valid one.
 

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:41.380
The state, property,
and capital;

00:17:41.380 --> 00:17:43.118
back to Smith.
 

00:17:43.118 --> 00:17:48.210
Smith famously talked about the
night watchmen's fate,

00:17:48.210 --> 00:17:53.011
the state which focuses
primarily on law and order,

00:17:53.011 --> 00:17:56.470
and the enforcement of
contract;

00:17:56.470 --> 00:18:03.026
the state which makes it
possible for a person to own

00:18:03.026 --> 00:18:06.415
property,
to deploy that property

00:18:06.415 --> 00:18:10.928
productively,
and to make money by satisfying

00:18:10.928 --> 00:18:14.108
the apparent needs of others.
 

00:18:14.108 --> 00:18:19.257
Now in order to have a night
watchmen state you better have a

00:18:19.257 --> 00:18:22.162
state,
and Smith wrote roughly two

00:18:22.162 --> 00:18:25.148
centuries,
a century and a half,

00:18:25.148 --> 00:18:28.838
after the Treaty of Westphalia
1648,

00:18:28.838 --> 00:18:33.229
which was the launch point of
the modern nation's state system

00:18:33.229 --> 00:18:36.180
with a monopoly on force and
violence,

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:41.804
and Smith is in a sense
building a theoretical system on

00:18:41.804 --> 00:18:47.019
the foundation of state-enforced
property rights.

00:18:47.019 --> 00:18:50.798
In fact, not just in a way,
that is what he does.

00:18:50.798 --> 00:18:54.460
These are the states involved
in that treaty.

00:18:54.460 --> 00:19:00.769
This is Thomas Hobbs whose
Leviathan is the defining

00:19:00.769 --> 00:19:06.955
tract on nation states,
and which defines the leviathan

00:19:06.955 --> 00:19:11.180
as a monopolist on force and
violence.

00:19:11.180 --> 00:19:17.432
We prevent being the victims of
one another by entrusting to the

00:19:17.432 --> 00:19:23.190
state a full monopoly on the use
of force and violence,

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:27.650
and in that way,
profit enormously through

00:19:27.650 --> 00:19:31.816
peace,
security, and the ability to

00:19:31.816 --> 00:19:37.618
plan ahead based on our current
property holdings.

00:19:37.618 --> 00:19:40.808
The nation state system lays
out like this.

00:19:40.808 --> 00:19:45.007
It is in many ways,
I think you can say this

00:19:45.007 --> 00:19:49.303
definitively,
capitalism without the nation's

00:19:49.303 --> 00:19:52.328
state system is infeasible.
 

00:19:52.328 --> 00:19:57.433
That if there were not the
coercive agency of the state in

00:19:57.433 --> 00:20:02.269
the background to vouch safe
property and contract,

00:20:02.269 --> 00:20:06.288
to perform the functions de
Soto attributes to it,

00:20:06.288 --> 00:20:10.584
if it were not for that,
then none of the capital

00:20:10.584 --> 00:20:15.594
formation processes that are
vital to our wealth would be

00:20:15.594 --> 00:20:17.920
reliable and feasible.
 

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:21.900
Now you could invent some
entirely different system.

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:26.395
You could invent a system which
sliced the world on another

00:20:26.395 --> 00:20:30.893
angle, conceivably a functional
angle, or could be a gender

00:20:30.893 --> 00:20:33.220
organization in the world.
 

00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:36.558
There could be a state for
women and a state for men,

00:20:36.558 --> 00:20:39.913
the geography of it would be a
little tangled but they're going

00:20:39.913 --> 00:20:43.777
to reproduce,
but the gist of this is that

00:20:43.777 --> 00:20:50.199
capitalist wealth rests on the
foundation of the nation state

00:20:50.199 --> 00:20:55.873
system and the nation state
system is not altogether a

00:20:55.873 --> 00:20:57.798
pretty story.
 

00:20:57.798 --> 00:21:02.365
Here's the British Empire as it
stood in 1920,

00:21:02.365 --> 00:21:06.727
or the 1920s,
and none of these places shown

00:21:06.727 --> 00:21:11.798
in red volunteered to join the
British Empire.

00:21:11.798 --> 00:21:15.858
Now you might claim that
Australia and New Zealand did,

00:21:15.858 --> 00:21:18.490
I think, but even that's a
reach.

00:21:18.490 --> 00:21:23.396
The British Empire was an
extremely coercive device for

00:21:23.396 --> 00:21:28.487
occupying territories and
extracting from their economies

00:21:28.487 --> 00:21:32.848
a vast surplus for the
metropolitan country.

00:21:32.848 --> 00:21:37.180
It had many knock on effects
which worked out well.

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:42.327
The--much of the infrastructure
and educational systems which

00:21:42.327 --> 00:21:47.388
makes India so promising today
is partly related to the best

00:21:47.388 --> 00:21:53.683
parts of British raj,
but the colonial background is

00:21:53.683 --> 00:21:58.288
a part of the nation state
story.

00:21:58.288 --> 00:22:06.990
The function of states having
no state versus a state,

00:22:06.990 --> 00:22:10.170
having a failed state versus an
effective state,

00:22:10.170 --> 00:22:15.239
having a state which fails to
promote formal property versus

00:22:15.239 --> 00:22:20.630
one that does,
the one point in the tree which

00:22:20.630 --> 00:22:28.111
leads to the existence of what
de Soto calls live capital is

00:22:28.111 --> 00:22:33.037
this one,
and lucky for you and me,

00:22:33.037 --> 00:22:40.638
it is the one which envelops
our lives in the United States

00:22:40.638 --> 00:22:44.308
and in the western world.
 

00:22:44.308 --> 00:22:49.163
The--and de Soto's thesis
really boils down to this

00:22:49.163 --> 00:22:54.019
two-by-two table with dead
versus live capital,

00:22:54.019 --> 00:22:56.890
and formal versus informal
property rights,

00:22:56.890 --> 00:23:00.938
but in the back of this is the
notion that you have to have a

00:23:00.938 --> 00:23:04.311
state which effectively and
efficiently administers

00:23:04.311 --> 00:23:05.190
property.
 

00:23:05.190 --> 00:23:10.088
And that means an elaborate
court system,

00:23:10.088 --> 00:23:12.730
a vast number of lawyers,
barristers,

00:23:12.730 --> 00:23:16.950
and the like,
a huge recordkeeping system,

00:23:16.950 --> 00:23:24.930
and a--and behind it all a
government capable of enforcing

00:23:24.930 --> 00:23:31.930
property rights against theft
and expropriation.

00:23:31.930 --> 00:23:35.390
This map of this neighborhood
of New Haven,

00:23:35.390 --> 00:23:37.750
the green lines are the
property lines,

00:23:37.750 --> 00:23:42.673
and the vault at 200 Orange
Street contains the records

00:23:42.673 --> 00:23:46.960
corresponding to each of the
green polygons,

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:51.537
and in the city there are
26,000 and some green polygons

00:23:51.537 --> 00:23:55.726
like that,
and the whole surface of North

00:23:55.726 --> 00:24:01.008
America is covered with
analogous polygons which are

00:24:01.008 --> 00:24:04.839
seed points of capital
formation,

00:24:04.839 --> 00:24:14.108
and energize the economy.
 

00:24:14.108 --> 00:24:19.059
Now de Soto constructs a
strategy of conversion from dead

00:24:19.059 --> 00:24:24.127
capital to live,
toward the back part of the

00:24:24.127 --> 00:24:28.519
book with these phases
indicated,

00:24:28.519 --> 00:24:32.730
and in many parts of the world,
in much of Latin America,

00:24:32.730 --> 00:24:35.450
much of Africa,
some parts of Asia,

00:24:35.450 --> 00:24:43.432
the campaign to create live
capital is a very real and live

00:24:43.432 --> 00:24:48.070
campaign today,
and is strategically of

00:24:48.070 --> 00:24:50.420
considerable importance.
 

00:24:50.420 --> 00:24:54.730
As you think ahead to the case
you're going to write about,

00:24:54.730 --> 00:24:57.569
in Cochabamba,
Bolivia, and about which we'll

00:24:57.569 --> 00:25:01.380
have a few minutes to talk
toward the end of this class,

00:25:01.380 --> 00:25:08.576
the very informality of that
economy is part of what kills

00:25:08.576 --> 00:25:13.500
Bechtel and its development
projects.

00:25:13.500 --> 00:25:18.573
De Soto makes quite a lot of
how it is that you can't have an

00:25:18.573 --> 00:25:22.970
informal system of property and
then just impose,

00:25:22.970 --> 00:25:25.876
cookie cutter style,
a formal system of property

00:25:25.876 --> 00:25:29.584
which no one understands,
and which doesn't correspond to

00:25:29.584 --> 00:25:30.538
their beliefs.
 

00:25:30.538 --> 00:25:34.690
You've got to adapt the formal
system to the informal system,

00:25:34.690 --> 00:25:37.470
and if de Soto is right and I
think he is,

00:25:37.470 --> 00:25:42.259
part of the brilliance of
American property law was that

00:25:42.259 --> 00:25:45.568
it found ways to incorporate
again,

00:25:45.568 --> 00:25:50.310
and again, and again to
incorporate informal property

00:25:50.310 --> 00:25:55.768
rights like the Tomahawk farm,
or the miners' rights recorded

00:25:55.768 --> 00:26:00.257
in miners' association records
having no relationship to

00:26:00.257 --> 00:26:01.400
government.
 

00:26:01.400 --> 00:26:03.119
Government didn't come along
and say,

00:26:03.119 --> 00:26:05.582
"No that's all baloney,
we're going to do it our

00:26:05.582 --> 00:26:07.420
way," government came along
and said,

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:11.079
"Oh we see,
now let's put that into

00:26:11.079 --> 00:26:15.680
language which can be
incorporated in the law,

00:26:15.680 --> 00:26:21.866
and which can allow the law to
work with rather than against

00:26:21.866 --> 00:26:27.215
the property rights which you
have established among

00:26:27.215 --> 00:26:28.788
yourselves.
 

00:26:28.788 --> 00:26:40.680
Ron Coase, Coase is a Chicago
School economist and a--

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:45.410
and he's written--he wrote all
kinds of wonderful scholarship,

00:26:45.410 --> 00:26:49.118
and what's called the Coase
Theorem is really post hoc

00:26:49.118 --> 00:26:51.288
reinterpretation of his work.
 

00:26:51.288 --> 00:26:55.261
He never sat down to write a
paper called "my

00:26:55.261 --> 00:26:58.910
theorem,"
and the insight in it is really

00:26:58.910 --> 00:27:03.675
pretty straightforward,
and I make it a little simpler

00:27:03.675 --> 00:27:05.588
than he would like it.
 

00:27:05.588 --> 00:27:10.338
But as we said before,
where there are clear initial

00:27:10.338 --> 00:27:14.512
entitlements,
where the entitlements and the

00:27:14.512 --> 00:27:18.538
opportunity to change them are
transparent,

00:27:18.538 --> 00:27:22.743
and where the information is
shared in a way that is

00:27:22.743 --> 00:27:27.855
relatively symmetrical so that
we don't have situations where a

00:27:27.855 --> 00:27:32.721
buyer or a broker knows all
kinds of things which a customer

00:27:32.721 --> 00:27:36.539
doesn't know--
I said that wrong--where an

00:27:36.539 --> 00:27:41.282
owner or a broker knows all
kinds of things which a customer

00:27:41.282 --> 00:27:43.731
doesn't know;
and finally,

00:27:43.731 --> 00:27:45.960
low transaction costs.
 

00:27:45.960 --> 00:27:48.935
A practical story;
have any of you ever been

00:27:48.935 --> 00:27:53.460
involved in a buying a house or
being part of a family as it

00:27:53.460 --> 00:27:54.839
bought a house?
 

00:27:54.839 --> 00:27:57.079
Yes.
 

00:27:57.079 --> 00:27:59.308
Okay, that's informative.
 

00:27:59.308 --> 00:28:02.843
Did you--what did you do to
remedy the information asymmetry

00:28:02.843 --> 00:28:04.578
between you and the seller?
 

00:28:04.578 --> 00:28:06.509
Student:  I didn't do
anything.

00:28:06.509 --> 00:28:09.738
Prof: You didn't do
anything, but what did your

00:28:09.738 --> 00:28:10.470
family do?
 

00:28:10.470 --> 00:28:11.559
Student:  Visited the
house.

00:28:11.559 --> 00:28:14.890
Prof: Okay and just that?
 

00:28:14.890 --> 00:28:16.769
Student:  I'm sure they
had all sorts of papers but--

00:28:16.769 --> 00:28:20.886
Prof: I hope what they
did was hired someone to inspect

00:28:20.886 --> 00:28:23.250
the house and give them a
report.

00:28:23.250 --> 00:28:26.858
Let's check with the
gentle--behind you.

00:28:26.858 --> 00:28:28.450
Do you have experience with
this?

00:28:28.450 --> 00:28:29.960
Student:  Yes.
 

00:28:29.960 --> 00:28:31.965
Prof: And--
Student:  We had it

00:28:31.965 --> 00:28:32.380
appraised.
 

00:28:32.380 --> 00:28:33.559
Prof: Okay you had an
appraisal.

00:28:33.559 --> 00:28:34.358
Student:  Yeah.
 

00:28:34.358 --> 00:28:36.719
Prof: And did you have
anybody look at the pipes,

00:28:36.719 --> 00:28:38.349
and the roof,
and the--and all that?

00:28:38.349 --> 00:28:38.630
Student:  Yeah.
 

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:40.390
Prof: Good I'm glad.
 

00:28:40.390 --> 00:28:44.068
The--there's a--I say this
because I,

00:28:44.068 --> 00:28:48.125
four or five years ago bought a
house with a slate roof and I

00:28:48.125 --> 00:28:51.912
got a report which called the
condition of the slate roof

00:28:51.912 --> 00:28:53.670
"very good."
 

00:28:53.670 --> 00:28:56.163
Well it turns out that
"very good"

00:28:56.163 --> 00:28:59.529
for a slate roof costs about
$20,000 a year in repairs,

00:28:59.529 --> 00:29:02.278
so it was a very bad decision
on my part,

00:29:02.278 --> 00:29:08.855
but the information symmetry
part of this is central and the

00:29:08.855 --> 00:29:13.868
idea is that you can get
efficient market,

00:29:13.868 --> 00:29:18.271
including an efficient
formation of capital through

00:29:18.271 --> 00:29:23.380
leveraging real property where
those conditions are met.

00:29:23.380 --> 00:29:28.471
So as a practical guide in
doing things you get three

00:29:28.471 --> 00:29:34.444
things to tick on your fingers
and think about in managing the

00:29:34.444 --> 00:29:38.460
affairs of an organization or a
firm.

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:44.977
This is too complicated;
the rough idea here is to take

00:29:44.977 --> 00:29:50.134
the three factors in Coase and
run them against the obvious

00:29:50.134 --> 00:29:54.759
aspects of the nation state
system and look how--

00:29:54.759 --> 00:30:01.082
take an example technology
transfer relates to transparency

00:30:01.082 --> 00:30:07.185
so that where one segment of
society has unique access to

00:30:07.185 --> 00:30:12.308
technology and knowledge that
others lack,

00:30:12.308 --> 00:30:16.301
you can assume there will be
huge asymmetries in the

00:30:16.301 --> 00:30:20.763
distribution of information and
that that will distort the

00:30:20.763 --> 00:30:25.848
functioning of the economy,
and sure enough it does,

00:30:25.848 --> 00:30:31.865
and part of the justification
for government provision of

00:30:31.865 --> 00:30:37.991
public education is that it
provides the minimum access to

00:30:37.991 --> 00:30:44.547
information and the methods of
obtaining information which are

00:30:44.547 --> 00:30:51.640
required by citizenship in a
democratic and market society.

00:30:51.640 --> 00:30:55.477
With any market economy you're
going to expect to move

00:30:55.477 --> 00:30:57.650
northeast of the status quo.
 

00:30:57.650 --> 00:31:01.972
I did an elaborate exercise
with Edgeworth boxes with you

00:31:01.972 --> 00:31:05.680
about a month ago,
and where you start determines

00:31:05.680 --> 00:31:07.068
where you end.
 

00:31:07.068 --> 00:31:11.593
So if we start here,
where the Smith's have almost

00:31:11.593 --> 00:31:16.670
everything, we're going to end
up somewhere up there.

00:31:16.670 --> 00:31:18.823
Or here where the Joneses own
almost everything,

00:31:18.823 --> 00:31:20.608
we're going to end up somewhere
here.

00:31:20.608 --> 00:31:25.962
So what Coase doesn't say is
that there is some particular

00:31:25.962 --> 00:31:31.130
symmetry or justice to the way
property rights move,

00:31:31.130 --> 00:31:35.240
and indeed, it's worth stopping
to say that to ourselves.

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:40.842
Whomsoever expects social
justice from a market economy

00:31:40.842 --> 00:31:42.710
expects in vain.
 

00:31:42.710 --> 00:31:45.038
That's not what market
economies are good at,

00:31:45.038 --> 00:31:52.840
they're good at a lot of
things, but you cannot when you

00:31:52.840 --> 00:32:00.317
are a wealthy septuagenarian,
and I'm at least one of those

00:32:00.317 --> 00:32:06.701
two, you cannot say to yourself
that it is the just verdict that

00:32:06.701 --> 00:32:11.970
the American economy that I
should be well to do.

00:32:11.970 --> 00:32:16.328
It has in it all kinds of
happenstance factors,

00:32:16.328 --> 00:32:22.523
including the luck of one's
birth, and the generosity of

00:32:22.523 --> 00:32:27.480
one's educators that those
things happen,

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:33.588
and so the claim I--people,
I am clearly pro-capitalist,

00:32:33.588 --> 00:32:36.259
but when I argue with people
and they say,

00:32:36.259 --> 00:32:38.570
"Well you know there are
all kinds of people who have

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:40.962
more money than they deserve and
others who have less,"

00:32:40.962 --> 00:32:42.690
I say,
"Yes, I agree,

00:32:42.690 --> 00:32:47.068
and there may be other remedies
you want to take for that."

00:32:47.068 --> 00:32:51.112
For example,
giving some people some of your

00:32:51.112 --> 00:32:56.189
own money, but the claim for
capitalism just doesn't go

00:32:56.189 --> 00:32:57.130
there.
 

00:32:57.130 --> 00:33:00.838
Wealth maximizing law and the
joint stock corporation;

00:33:00.838 --> 00:33:06.150
the law that government creates
can either be well designed or

00:33:06.150 --> 00:33:10.678
poorly designed to create
wealth, and we started some

00:33:10.678 --> 00:33:13.288
months ago with Ghen v.
 

00:33:13.288 --> 00:33:18.232
Rich, the matter of a
sinking whale and the tailoring

00:33:18.232 --> 00:33:23.616
of the judgment in that case to
preserve the incentive for the

00:33:23.616 --> 00:33:28.324
whaling industry,
by allowing the principle gains

00:33:28.324 --> 00:33:33.048
to go to those who take the
largest risks and make the

00:33:33.048 --> 00:33:37.685
largest investment and that's
the intuition of wealth

00:33:37.685 --> 00:33:39.470
maximizing law.
 

00:33:39.470 --> 00:33:42.917
Another case we I think looked
at, I'm not quite sure,

00:33:42.917 --> 00:33:44.023
did we do U.S.
 

00:33:44.023 --> 00:33:44.348
v.
 

00:33:44.348 --> 00:33:46.750
Cosby, the one about air
rights?

00:33:46.750 --> 00:33:48.038
Well you get it.
 

00:33:48.038 --> 00:33:51.896
Before the airplane it was
perfectly sensible to say that

00:33:51.896 --> 00:33:55.755
the air rights over one's land
extended to the end of the

00:33:55.755 --> 00:33:59.489
universe,
or at least until they got to

00:33:59.489 --> 00:34:02.640
the next inhabited solar system.
 

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:06.230
That was a perfectly okay thing
to say and did no harm,

00:34:06.230 --> 00:34:10.659
but once air travel became part
of the technology,

00:34:10.659 --> 00:34:14.853
it had to change that precept
and grant the right of free

00:34:14.853 --> 00:34:17.550
trespass above a certain
altitude.

00:34:17.550 --> 00:34:24.527
This is Marc Lanier;
did I show you guys a little

00:34:24.527 --> 00:34:25.820
bit of Marc Lanier?
 

00:34:25.820 --> 00:34:30.480
Okay and the dark side of
wealth max--the top side of

00:34:30.480 --> 00:34:35.139
wealth maximizing law is tort
law and the lawsuit.

00:34:35.139 --> 00:34:40.536
But the thinking behind having
lawsuits is that lawsuits

00:34:40.536 --> 00:34:46.422
provide an incentive against
carelessness in dealing with the

00:34:46.422 --> 00:34:51.623
lives of others and the
punishment that a company gets

00:34:51.623 --> 00:34:56.920
for producing a hazardous
product or performing a risky

00:34:56.920 --> 00:35:02.905
and failed medical procedure is
a way of keeping manufacturers

00:35:02.905 --> 00:35:07.909
and healthcare people honest and
careful.

00:35:07.909 --> 00:35:18.860
The critical features of the
joint stock corporation,

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:22.135
as compared with
straightforward proprietorship

00:35:22.135 --> 00:35:25.349
and partnership,
are first of all that the chain

00:35:25.349 --> 00:35:26.969
of accountability is thin.
 

00:35:26.969 --> 00:35:30.989
That is the customer's and
investors;

00:35:30.989 --> 00:35:35.431
both have only a thin
relationship with the decision

00:35:35.431 --> 00:35:37.260
makers in the firm.
 

00:35:37.260 --> 00:35:41.523
If you owned 1,000 shares of
General Motors and you think

00:35:41.523 --> 00:35:44.949
they shouldn't have fired Fritz
yesterday,

00:35:44.949 --> 00:35:47.182
as they did,
you're going to waste your

00:35:47.182 --> 00:35:49.768
money by calling them up to talk
about it.

00:35:49.768 --> 00:35:52.855
If you're the owner of a
General Motors car and you don't

00:35:52.855 --> 00:35:55.280
like the way the door handles
are put on,

00:35:55.280 --> 00:35:58.884
it's not much use calling them
up and asking them to do it

00:35:58.884 --> 00:35:59.768
differently.
 

00:35:59.768 --> 00:36:04.070
What you have to do is buy
another manufacturer's car.

00:36:04.070 --> 00:36:06.869
The role of ownership is
passive.

00:36:06.869 --> 00:36:12.735
The investors buy shares and if
they don't like the course of

00:36:12.735 --> 00:36:17.429
the company's management they
sell the shares.

00:36:17.429 --> 00:36:21.463
Liability is limited;
the most that an investor can

00:36:21.463 --> 00:36:25.737
lose is what she put into the
shares that she purchased,

00:36:25.737 --> 00:36:28.690
and that's a great provision
right.

00:36:28.690 --> 00:36:33.047
If you're an investor it means
that you really don't have to do

00:36:33.047 --> 00:36:35.929
much homework,
at least homework about the

00:36:35.929 --> 00:36:38.530
downside of management
practices.

00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:40.510
Liquidity is like water.
 

00:36:40.510 --> 00:36:44.686
It is a perfectly liquid
instrument and it is an

00:36:44.686 --> 00:36:49.590
endlessly scalable instrument,
and the joint stock corporation

00:36:49.590 --> 00:36:53.871
is about--
between 88% to 90% of a market

00:36:53.871 --> 00:36:59.719
economy is embodied in joint
stock corporations.

00:36:59.719 --> 00:37:03.210
Whenever there are flaws,
and their flaws are many,

00:37:03.210 --> 00:37:06.239
Jim Alexander here has told you
of a few,

00:37:06.239 --> 00:37:12.376
their flaws are many but the
ability to produce at enormous

00:37:12.376 --> 00:37:15.612
scale,
with enormous efficiency,

00:37:15.612 --> 00:37:16.889
is very real.
 

